1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8.
Na3 b5 9. Nd5 Be7 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. c4 {Thanks to Morozevich's efforts this
system has lately become one of the most fashionable ways to meet the
Sveshnikov Sicilian.} b4 12. Nc2 a5 13. g3 ({One year ago in the World Blitz
Championship the game between the same opponents continued} 13. Qf3 Bg5 (13...
Be7 $142) 14. h4 Bh6 15. g4 f6 16. g5 ({The next day Morozevich improved:} 16.
Rg1 O-O 17. Qg3 g6 18. g5 fxg5 19. hxg5 Bg7 20. O-O-O a4 21. c5 $16 {1-0
Morozevich,A (2755)-Carlsen,M (2714)/Moscow (blitz) 2007 (41)}) 16... fxg5 17.
hxg5 Qxg5 18. Rxh6 gxh6 19. Nc7+ Ke7 20. Nxa8 Bg4 21. Qd3 Rxa8 22. Qd5 Rc8 {
0-1 Morozevich,A (2755)-Shirov,A (2739)/Moscow (blitz) 2007 (46): with good
play for Black:}) ({The other way to develop pieces} 13. Be2 {followed by 0-0
and Qd3 is preferred by Kamsky.}) 13... O-O 14. h4 Be6 15. Bg2 $146 {
Previously in this system h2-h4 has always been followed by Bh3. However, the
idea to place the bishop on g2 after having played h2-h4 is a rather common
plan in the systems with the pawn on c3 instead of c4 (11.c3). The pawn on h4
prevents Bf6-g5 and is a useful move in most cases anyway.} ({A few months
prior to the present game, after the standard} 15. Bh3 {Shirov found a way to
exploit his development advantage with the new idea} a4 $1 {using the fact
that White cannot quickly find a safe place for his king. Black obtained
promising play after} 16. Ncxb4 (16. Kf1 b3 $36) 16... Nxb4 17. Bxe6 fxe6 18.
Nxb4 Qb6 19. Qd2 Be7 20. a3 Rf3 21. Rf1 Raf8 $44 {1-0 Nisipeanu,L (2684)
-Shirov,A (2740)/Foros 2008 (36).}) 15... g6 $5 {Having some lead in
development Shirov is not afraid of a possible attack on the h-file.} (15... a4
{is still an option, although with the bishop on g2 it's less attractive since
White would simply castle} 16. O-O {and Black still has some problems to solve:
his bishop can't go to g5, while the queenside pawns need protection. A
possible follow-up is} (16. Ncxb4 $6 Nxb4 17. Nxb4 Qa5 18. a3 Bxc4 {again
leaves White with the king in the center}) 16... b3 17. axb3 (17. Nce3 $5)
17... axb3 18. Rxa8 Qxa8 19. Nxf6+ gxf6 20. Ne3 Nd4 21. f4 $5 $36) 16. Nxf6+ {
Otherwise the bishop will retreat to g7.} ({After} 16. h5 Bg5 {White doesn't
have direct ways to develop an attack, since} 17. f4 exf4 18. gxf4 Bh4+ 19. Kf1
g5 {[%cal Gf7f5]} 20. f5 Ne5 $132 {is hardly the position White is aiming for
[%csl Gf1]}) (16. O-O Bg7 $11) 16... Qxf6 17. b3 (17. Qxd6 $2 Rac8 18. Ne3 Rfd8
19. Qc5 Nd4 20. Qb6 Qe7 {and White is in trouble: apart from the complete lack
of coordination between his pieces, the queen on b6 can easily be trapped:} 21.
O-O Rb8 22. Qxa5 Ra8 23. Qxe5 ({or} 23. Qb6 Rdb8 $19) 23... f6 24. Qf4 Ne2+) (
17. Ne3 {releases control over the d4-square, allowing} Nd4) (17. Qd3 Rfc8 18.
O-O $140 $2 Bxc4 19. Qxc4 Nd4 $17) 17... a4 {Black must try to create activity
on the a-file if he wishes to avoid a passive position. Shirov rightly decided
that there is no point in delaying the advance of the a-pawn, although it
should be added that such a decision has certain drawbacks, since the advance
of the a-pawn always weakens the pawn on b4.} 18. O-O (18. Qxd6 $2 {loses
again:} axb3 19. axb3 (19. Qxc6 bxc2 $19) 19... Nd4 $1 20. Rc1 Nxc2+ 21. Rxc2
Ra1+ 22. Ke2 Bg4+ {followed by 23...Qxd6}) 18... axb3 {An understandable
desire to release the tension and distract the queen from the d-file (and thus
not have to worry about the d-pawn).} ({The alternative} 18... Qe7 19. Qd2 Qb7
20. h5 (20. Qxd6 Rfd8 21. Qc5 Rd2 22. Rfc1 (22. Rac1 axb3 23. axb3 Ra2 $17)
22... axb3 23. axb3 Rxa1 24. Nxa1 Nd4 $44) 20... Ra7 $1 {leads to a
complicated middlegame: White has possibilities to develop an initiative on
